TELEGRAM_CHAT_ID

This determines where the bot sends the "/gm" message. The process depends on whether you're using a private chat, a group, or a channel.

Private chat (the easiest option)

1. Find your bot by username in Telegram and send it any message, for example "/start".
   Bots cannot see messages until the user contacts them first.

2. Open the following URL in your browser:
   
   "https://api.telegram.org/bot<YOUR_TOKEN>/getUpdates"

3. In the JSON response, find:
   
   ""chat":{"id":123456789,...}"
   
   That number is your "TELEGRAM_CHAT_ID".

Group chat

1. Add the bot to the group.
2. Send any message in the group.
3. Open the same "getUpdates" URL and look for the group's "chat.id".

Group IDs are negative numbers, for example:

"-123456789"

Channel or supergroup

1. Add the bot as an administrator of the channel or supergroup.
   Without admin permissions, "sendMessage" will not work.
2. Publish any post or message.
3. Check "getUpdates".

Channel and supergroup IDs usually look like:

"-100xxxxxxxxxx"

Faster alternative

Instead of manually parsing JSON, you can simply message @userinfobot or @RawDataBot in Telegram.

They will immediately reply with your numeric "chat_id".

For groups, temporarily add one of these bots to the group, retrieve the group ID, and remove the bot afterwards.

