Strategy parameters

These values are not tied to any external service — you choose them yourself.

Variable| Description| How to choose
"DRY_RUN"| "true" or "false"| Keep this set to "true" until you've confirmed from the logs that the bot is finding reasonable pairs and spreads. Switch to "false" only when you're confident it's behaving as expected.
"LEVERAGE"| Leverage used on both legs| "10x" is what you originally requested. Keep in mind that higher leverage means a smaller price divergence is enough to trigger liquidation on one side of the trade, and the bot does not automatically close positions.
"NOTIONAL_USDT" / "NOTIONAL_USDC"| Position size per leg in dollars| "100/100" matches the original configuration. Actual order size is also limited by the instrument's "minOrderQty" on Bybit. If the asset price is high and your notional value is too small, the order may fail due to minimum quantity requirements.
"ENTRY_SPREAD_PCT"| Entry threshold as a fraction ("0.004 = 0.4%")| A good starting point is your taker fee multiplied by two (since both legs pay fees), plus some extra margin for funding rate differences between USDT and USDC perpetual contracts. Otherwise, an apparent spread may disappear after fees and funding costs.
"POLL_INTERVAL_SECS"| Market polling frequency| "3" seconds is a reasonable balance between responsiveness and Bybit rate limits. Public market endpoints are rate-limited per IP address, so polling too aggressively across many symbols can trigger "429" or "retCode" errors in the logs.

